        content:
          "Cross-examination is not just a Q&A session — it is a strategic battleground where control determines who wins. The debater who controls the flow of cross-examination dictates the pace, direction, and outcome of the exchange. When you control CX, you decide which topics get discussed, how long each topic gets explored, and where the conversation leads. Your opponent is forced to respond on your terms rather than setting their own agenda.\n\nMany debaters mistakenly treat CX as an unstructured conversation where both sides freely exchange ideas. In reality, the best debaters approach CX with a clear plan. They know exactly what admissions they want to extract, which topics to push on, and when to move on. Think of yourself as a skilled interviewer — you have an outline, you guide the conversation, and you redirect when the other person tries to go off-topic. This kind of deliberate control separates average debaters from truly dominant ones.\n\nIn this lesson, you will learn specific techniques for maintaining control during cross-examination. We will cover how to manage pacing, steer topics, handle evasive answers, and use follow-up questions to keep your opponent on the defensive. These skills apply whether you are the questioner or the answerer — control is about mindset and technique, not just who is asking the questions.",
