        content:
          "**Why Pacing Matters**\n\nPacing is the most fundamental element of CX control. The speed at which questions are asked and answered shapes the entire dynamic of the exchange. When you control the pace, you control how much time your opponent has to think, how comfortable they feel, and how the judge perceives the exchange. A debater who sets a confident, steady pace appears more prepared and authoritative than one who seems to be reacting to whatever comes their way.\n\n**Fast Pacing Techniques**\n\nQuick, pointed questions are ideal when you want to pin down an opponent before they can formulate an evasive answer. Ask short yes-or-no questions in rapid succession: 'Your plan requires federal funding, correct?' followed immediately by 'And Congress hasn't approved that funding, correct?' followed by 'So implementation depends on future Congressional action, yes?' This rapid-fire approach builds a chain of admissions before your opponent realizes where you are heading. It works especially well against opponents who tend to give long, rambling answers — the short format of your questions makes their lengthy responses seem evasive.\n\n**Slow Pacing Techniques**\n\nSometimes slowing down is more powerful than speeding up. When you have just gotten a damaging admission, pause for a moment before your next question. Let the admission hang in the air so the judge can absorb it. You can also slow down when asking a particularly important question — the change in pace signals to the judge that something significant is about to happen. Strategic pauses also give you time to think about your next move, especially when an opponent gives an unexpected answer that requires you to adapt your question chain.",
