        content:
          "**Why Follow-Ups Matter**\n\nFollow-up questions are where CX control becomes truly powerful. A single question rarely produces a useful concession on its own — it is the follow-up that pins the opponent down and forces them to commit to a position. Without follow-ups, opponents can give vague, non-committal answers and escape without any damage. With follow-ups, you force clarity and precision, which either produces a useful admission or exposes evasiveness that the judge will notice.\n\n**Types of Follow-Up Questions**\n\nThe most effective follow-up is the **clarification follow-up**: 'When you say \"significant impact,\" can you give me a specific number or range?' This forces precision. The **implication follow-up** takes their answer and extends it: 'So if your impact is limited to X, then your advantage is smaller than our disadvantage, correct?' The **consistency follow-up** compares their answer to something else they have said: 'But earlier in your constructive, you said Y. How does that fit with what you just told me?' Each type serves a different strategic purpose.\n\n**Demanding Direct Answers**\n\nWhen an opponent is being evasive, you have several tools. The most direct is simply saying, 'Can you answer yes or no?' If they insist on qualifying, you can say, 'I will give you time to explain, but first, is the basic answer yes or no?' This approach is respectful but firm — you are not cutting off their explanation, just asking for the core answer first. Judges generally respect this technique because it shows you are seeking clarity, not trying to silence your opponent. If they still refuse to give a direct answer, that evasiveness itself becomes an argument you can make in your next speech: 'They refused to answer a simple yes-or-no question, which tells you they know the answer hurts their case.'",
