          "**Control Is Not Only for Questioners**\n\nMany debaters assume that the questioner always has control during CX, but that is a myth. Skilled answerers can maintain significant control by choosing how they frame their responses, how much detail they provide, and when they push back on unfair questions. The key is to answer honestly and directly while protecting your case — you never want to lie or dodge, but you can absolutely choose the most strategic way to tell the truth.\n\n**Strategic Answering Techniques**\n\nThe **qualified answer** adds necessary context: instead of saying 'Yes, our plan costs more,' you say 'Our plan has higher upfront costs, but those are offset by long-term savings that their plan does not achieve.' The **bridge answer** acknowledges the question but redirects to your strength: 'That is a fair question, and the answer actually highlights why our approach is better, because...' The **reframe** corrects a misleading premise: 'That question assumes X, but actually the situation is Y, so the answer is...' Each technique lets you answer honestly while ensuring the judge hears your side of the story.\n\n**Setting Boundaries as an Answerer**\n\nYou have the right to push back on unfair questions. If a question contains a false premise, say so: 'I do not accept the premise of that question. Our plan does not do X, so I cannot answer as if it does.' If a question is actually a statement, point it out: 'That sounds more like an argument than a question. Would you like to rephrase?' If you are being interrupted mid-answer, you can firmly say, 'I would like to finish my answer.' Judges respect answerers who stand their ground professionally — it shows confidence and command of the material.",
