          "**Planning Your CX Time Budget**\n\nCX time is limited, and every second counts. Before CX begins, you should have a rough time budget in mind. If you have three minutes of CX, plan to spend about 45 seconds to one minute on each of your two or three main question chains, with some buffer time for unexpected answers that require additional follow-up. This prevents the common mistake of spending all your CX time on one topic and never getting to your other prepared questions.\n\n**Adapting in Real Time**\n\nNo CX plan survives first contact completely intact. Your opponent may give unexpected answers, refuse to engage on certain topics, or say something so damaging that you want to pursue it further. The key is flexibility within structure — have your plan, but be willing to adapt. If you get a devastating admission early, it might be worth spending extra time locking it down rather than moving to your next planned topic. Conversely, if a line of questioning is going nowhere after 30 seconds, cut your losses and move on rather than wasting more time.\n\n**The Final Question**\n\nAlways plan your last question carefully. The final question of CX is what the judge remembers most vividly, so it should be your strongest or most damaging question. Some debaters save their best question chain for the end of CX so that the damaging admission leads directly into their next speech. Others use the final question as a summary: 'So just to confirm, you agreed that your plan has no funding mechanism, your impact is speculative, and your evidence is from 2015 — is that all correct?' This kind of recap question reinforces all the concessions you have built throughout CX.",
