        content:
          "Experienced debaters do not just ask random questions during cross-examination — they set traps. A CX trap is a sequence of questions designed to lead you into making a damaging admission that your opponent will then use against you in their speeches. The questions often seem innocent at first, but each one narrows your options until you are forced into a concession you did not intend to make. Recognizing these traps before you fall into them is a critical defensive skill.\n\nTraps work because of a psychological principle: once you start saying 'yes' to a series of reasonable-sounding questions, it becomes very difficult to suddenly say 'no' without seeming evasive or inconsistent. Skilled questioners exploit this by building question chains where each individual question sounds perfectly fair, but the cumulative effect leads to a devastating conclusion. If you are not actively watching for the trap, you will walk right into it.\n\nThis lesson will teach you to identify the most common CX trap patterns, understand why they work, and develop techniques for avoiding them without appearing evasive. The goal is not to refuse to answer questions — that hurts your credibility — but to answer in ways that prevent your opponent from using your responses against you. You can be honest and cooperative while still protecting your case from strategic traps.",
