          "**How It Works**\n\nThe overextension trap tempts you into claiming more than your evidence supports. Your opponent asks questions that invite you to expand or strengthen your claims: 'So your plan would solve this problem worldwide?' 'And it would work in every country?' 'And there would be no negative side effects at all?' Each question invites you to make a bolder claim, and if you agree, your opponent will later point out that your evidence only supports a much more limited claim. You have overextended your position, and now they can attack the gap between what you claimed and what you can prove.\n\n**Why Debaters Fall For It**\n\nDebaters fall for the overextension trap because saying 'yes, our plan does even more than we claimed' feels like winning. It seems like you are strengthening your case. But in reality, you are making claims you cannot support with evidence, and your opponent will exploit that gap. Judges are trained to notice when debaters claim more than their evidence proves, and overextension significantly damages your credibility. It is always better to accurately describe the scope of your claims than to overstate them.\n\n**How to Avoid It**\n\nWhen an opponent invites you to expand your claim, hold your ground at the level your evidence supports. Say, 'Our evidence shows our plan is effective in the domestic context we specified. We are not making global claims.' If they push, stay firm: 'I appreciate the interest in extending our analysis, but we are making the specific claim our evidence supports, and that claim is sufficient to win this debate.' This discipline shows the judge that you are a careful, honest advocate — which actually strengthens your credibility on the claims you do make.",
