          "**Exposure and Desensitization**\n\nComposure improves most reliably through repeated exposure to high-pressure CX situations. The more you experience tough cross-examination, the less threatening it feels. This is why experienced debaters seem naturally calm — they have simply been through enough stressful CX exchanges that the experience no longer triggers a strong stress response. You can accelerate this process through deliberate practice: have your debate partner aggressively cross-examine you during practice rounds, attend more tournaments, and volunteer for practice CX drills at your club.\n\n**Mindset Development**\n\nLong-term composure comes from developing a healthy relationship with pressure. Instead of viewing tough CX as a threat to avoid, view it as an opportunity to demonstrate your skills. The debaters who thrive under pressure are the ones who genuinely enjoy the challenge — they look forward to difficult questions because they know their answers will impress the judge. This mindset shift does not happen overnight, but it can be cultivated through positive self-talk, focusing on growth rather than perfection, and celebrating the moments when you handle pressure well.\n\n**Physical Habits That Support Composure**\n\nYour physical habits outside of debate affect your composure during rounds. Regular exercise reduces baseline anxiety. Adequate sleep improves emotional regulation. Avoiding excessive caffeine before rounds prevents jitteriness. Eating a balanced meal before tournaments keeps blood sugar stable. These seem like small things, but they create a physical foundation that makes it easier to stay calm when the pressure rises. The best debaters treat tournament preparation as a holistic process that includes both intellectual and physical readiness.",
