          "**Bringing CX Habits to Crossfire**\n\nThe most common mistake debaters make when switching formats is bringing CX habits into crossfire. They try to maintain complete questioner control in a format that does not support it, ask long question chains that get interrupted, or treat crossfire as if only one person should be asking questions. If you catch yourself trying to silence your opponent's questions during crossfire with 'I am asking the questions here,' you are applying CX norms to the wrong format. In crossfire, both sides have equal questioning rights.\n\n**Bringing Crossfire Habits to CX**\n\nThe reverse mistake is equally problematic. Debaters who primarily compete in PF sometimes try to ask counter-questions during CX when they are supposed to be answering: 'Well, let me ask YOU a question.' In traditional CX, this is not appropriate — the roles are fixed, and the answerer does not get to ask questions. They may also give overly brief answers (because crossfire rewards conciseness) when CX actually allows and sometimes requires more detailed responses. Understanding the norms of each format prevents these awkward moments.\n\n**The Adaptable Debater**\n\nThe most successful debaters across formats are those who can recognize which format they are in and adjust their approach accordingly. Before each CX or crossfire period, take a moment to mentally confirm the format and activate the appropriate skill set. With practice, this switch becomes automatic. Being format-adaptable is especially valuable if you compete in multiple events or switch formats between tournaments — it demonstrates versatility that will serve you well throughout your debate career.",
