          "**Short, Sharp Questions**\n\nIn 1v1 crossfire, your questions should be shorter and sharper than in traditional CX. Because your opponent can interject with their own questions at any time, you cannot afford to build long, complex question chains. Each question should be self-contained enough to be valuable even if you only get to ask one or two before the conversation shifts. 'Your impact depends on X happening — what evidence do you have that X will happen?' is a strong crossfire question because it challenges a specific claim and forces a substantive response, all in one question.\n\n**The Two-Question Chain**\n\nWhile long chains are risky in crossfire, short two-question chains are highly effective. Ask a setup question, then immediately follow with the payoff question: 'Your source for that claim is from 2019, correct?' (Setup.) 'So you are relying on data that predates the significant changes in this area that happened in 2021?' (Payoff.) The two-question chain is short enough that you can usually complete it before your opponent pivots, but long enough to make a substantive point. Practice developing two-question chains for each of your opponent's key arguments.\n\n**Asking Questions That Create Quotable Moments**\n\nThe most effective crossfire questions create moments you can reference in your next speech. You want your opponent to say something specific that you can quote: 'In crossfire, my opponent admitted that their impact estimate is uncertain.' To create these quotable moments, ask questions that require your opponent to make a specific concession or quantify their claims. 'How likely would you say your impact is — very likely, somewhat likely, or uncertain?' Any answer gives you something useful to reference later.",
