        title: "Defensive Crossfire: Answering and Counter-Questioning",
        content:
          "**The Answer-and-Counter Technique in Detail**\n\nThe most important technique in PF crossfire is the answer-and-counter. When your opponent asks a question, give a brief, substantive answer, then immediately pivot to your own question. For example: Opponent asks, 'Does your plan have implementation costs?' You answer: 'Yes, modest costs that are offset by savings. But let me ask you — how does your side address the harms we identified in our first contention?' This technique accomplishes three things: it answers the question honestly (maintaining credibility), it limits the time your opponent spends on offense (they cannot ask a follow-up because you have shifted to your own question), and it puts you on offense (now they have to respond to your question).\n\n**When Not to Counter-Question**\n\nThe answer-and-counter is powerful but should not be used after every single question. If you counter-question every time, it looks like you are dodging questions rather than engaging with them. Sometimes the best move is to give a thorough answer that directly addresses their concern and makes your case look strong. If their question actually highlights a strength in your position, take the time to explain fully: 'Actually, that is a great question because it lets me explain why our approach is specifically designed to handle that concern...' This shows engagement and confidence.\n\n**Handling Persistent Questioning**\n\nSometimes your opponent will refuse to accept your answer and keep pushing on the same point. In crossfire, you have more options than in CX. You can answer once, then say, 'I have answered that question. Let me ask you something.' If they persist, you can appeal to the format: 'Crossfire is a two-way exchange — I have answered your question, and I would like to ask mine.' This is a reasonable and professional way to maintain the balance of the crossfire format.",
