        content:
          "**PF Community Norms**\n\nPublic Forum debate has its own cultural norms around crossfire that differ from CX norms in Policy or LD. PF judges — especially lay judges and parent judges — expect crossfire to be accessible, professional, and respectful. Aggressive questioning styles that might be acceptable in Policy CX can alienate PF judges who are looking for civil discourse. Keep your tone conversational, avoid jargon, and treat your opponent as a respected colleague with a different viewpoint rather than an adversary to be defeated.\n\n**Managing Speaking Time Fairly**\n\nOne of the biggest crossfire challenges is ensuring both sides get roughly equal speaking time. Some debaters try to dominate crossfire by talking constantly — asking long questions, giving extended answers, and never pausing long enough for their opponent to speak. Judges notice this and view it negatively. Aim for a roughly 50/50 split in speaking time. Ask concise questions, give proportionate answers, and create natural openings for your opponent to speak. This does not mean being passive — you can be assertive and still fair.\n\n**What Judges Watch For**\n\nPF judges evaluate crossfire on several criteria: substance (are the questions and answers relevant and insightful?), demeanor (is the debater professional and composed?), engagement (is the debater actively listening and responding to what is actually said?), and clarity (can the judge follow the exchange easily?). The most common crossfire mistake is talking past your opponent rather than engaging with their actual arguments. When your opponent makes a point, respond to that specific point before moving on — judges want to see genuine engagement, not two people talking at each other.",
