          "**Trap Avoidance (All Formats)**\n\nRegardless of the format, you must watch for question traps: leading question chains (a series of 'yes' questions building to a damaging conclusion), false dilemmas (binary choices that both harm your case), loaded questions (hidden assumptions in the question itself), and overextension traps (invitations to claim more than your evidence supports). The universal defense is the same across all formats: recognize the pattern, add qualifications to your answers, and stay honest while protecting your case. The only difference is that in crossfire, you can disrupt traps by counter-questioning, which is not available in traditional CX.\n\n**Composure (All Formats)**\n\nMaintaining composure under pressure is critical in every questioning format. The techniques are universal: controlled breathing to counteract the stress response, mental resets to shift from threat mode to challenge mode, preparation-based confidence, calm responses to aggression, and recovery techniques when composure breaks occur. However, composure is tested differently in each format — in CX, the pressure comes from sustained, focused questioning; in crossfire, it comes from the chaotic, multi-directional nature of the exchange; and in grand crossfire, it comes from managing both your own responses and your partner's performance simultaneously.\n\n**Strategic Answering (All Formats)**\n\nQualified answers, bridges, reframes, and pivots work in every format. In CX, you have more time to develop thorough answers because the questioner controls the pace. In crossfire, your answers need to be more concise because you also need time to ask your own questions. In grand crossfire, your answers should be brief enough that your partner can add to them if needed. The core skill — answering honestly while protecting your case — remains the same; only the length and delivery style adapt to the format.",
